[misc]misc_677|[underline]Geology Lecture 3 1805[/underline][/misc]
The Science of Nature depends in a
great measure upon artificial inventions for
assisting the faculties of the mind and for
increasing the activity of genius.
And it requires for its advancement a State
of society in which active patronage is
offered; and in which it is assisted no less
by the diffusion of letters than by the
application of industry, riches and power
to its numerous and [deletion]diversified[/deletion]
diversified objects.-

[page]4|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00004|dnp16c02pp|94869421[/page]
It is not therefore [deletion]necessary[/deletion] extraordinary
that the [underline]spirit[/underline] of observation and of
experiment, which maintained with difficulty
a sickly existance even in the most [underline]splendid[/underline]
and happy eras of [place]place_155|Rome[/place], should have
disappeared altogether at the [unclear]time[/unclear] of Her
decline and degradation when turbulence
at Home, feebleness abroad and indulgence
in the grossest luxury had prepared the
way for the total downfall of the state
[place]place_475|Egypt[/place] recorded as the parent of Science
in the most remote antiquity was destined

[page]5|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00005|dnp16c03pp|94869422[/page]
by a singular occurrence of circumstances
to become her [underline]nurse[/underline] in a later period
And philosophy driven from the West by
persecution by the ravages of Barbarians
and the tumult of savage warfare found
[underline]a transient refuge[/underline] within the walls [underline]of[/underline]
[underline][place]place_1135|Alexandria[/place].[/underline]
Towards the close of the fourth century
at the time when the [misc]misc_538|Goths[/misc] were conquering
the finest provinces of Europe and keeping
the Romans in continual alarm this city
enjoyed a profound peace and afforded
an asylum to Students from all parts
of [underline]the Empire[/underline] -

[page]6|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00006|dnp16c04pp|94869423[/page]
The School of [place]place_1135|Alexandria[/place] produced several
laborious Geometricians; but the greatest
ornament belonging to it and the most
Illustrious Philosopher was [person]person_1049|Hypatia[/person] daughter
of [person]person_1050|Theon[/person] -
This celebrated lady is said to have
been equally distinguished for Her skill
in Mathematical in general science
and in the knowledge of Nature and
of the Earth.
And that She applied herself to
experiment is evident from one of her
invention the [misc]misc_850|Hydrometer[/misc] the instrument

[page]7|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00007|dnp16c05pp|94869424[/page]
now in common use for ascertaining
the relative weights of fluids -
[person]person_1049|Hypatia[/person] taught after her fathers death
in her native city.- By the eloquence
and soundness of her doctrines she excited
the highest zeal for moral and intellectual
improvement amongst her disciples.
She was no less admirable for the grace
and loviliness of her person than for
talents and virtue and she shone with
greater lustre being as it were a
single brilliant Star in a night
of clouds and [underline]obscurity[/underline] -

[page]8|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00008|dnp16c06pp|94869425[/page]
Learning flourished at [place]place_1135|Alexandria[/place] for nearly
two hundred years; but literature and metaphysics
seem to have been more attended to than
experimental knowledge -
of the improvement made however we are
almost wholly ignorant.
For the [insertion]same[/insertion] causes which put a stop to
the future progress of science destroyed all
the records of the advancement that had
been made.
The city was conquered by the [misc]misc_273|Saracens[/misc]
and the most magnificent and perfect
library in the world burnt by the
command of [person]person_1051|[underline]omar[/underline][/person]

[page]9|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00009|dnp16c07pp|94869426[/page]
Philosophy and letters were taken away
from the people and they were obliged
by the force of sword and of fire to
substitute for them the absurdities and
impostures of the [otherwork]otherwork_316|Koran.-[/otherwork]
All was again ignorance and darkness till
the eighth century when a feeble gleam
of light burst forth in [place]place_1212|Arabia[/place].
And the patronage of two celebrated Caliphs
[person]person_136|Al and[/person] [person]person_1052|Al kept alive[/person] for a
short time the spark of inquiry but at
this period there were no permanent materials
for it to act upon.
The spirit of Science and that of
[misc]misc_678|Mahometism[/misc] like the good and evil

[page]10|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00010|dnp16c08pp|94869427[/page]
principles of Zoraster were incapable of
being reconciled.
Improvement languished in the reign of
the later Sovereigns of [place]place_1311|Baghdad[/place] and it
perished altogether with the Empire
which was one of the first that fell
beneath the rising power of the Turks.
Very few words of importance have been
transmitted to us from the [misc]misc_273|Saracens[/misc], and
the details that we are in possession of
with regard to the short literary history
of this people are principally valuable
on account of their connection about
the time of the crusades with the

[page]11|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00011|dnp16c09pp|94869428[/page]
establishment of a particular [underline]philosophical[/underline]
sect in Europe which had the greatest
influence upon the progress of Natural
Science of chemistry and of Geology.
[person]person_1054|Gebir[/person] and [person]person_1053|Rhases[/person] of [place]place_1311|Bagdat[/place] are said
to have been the first men who
pursued the applications of Chemistry with the
view of ascertaining the nature of the
bodies belonging to the Earth and for
effecting changes in them -
And they are the philosophers to whom
the earliest Alchemists of the West
ascribe the origin of their Art.
Alchemy as at first professed was considered
as an universal [underline]Science[/underline]

[page]12|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00012|dnp16c10pp|94869429[/page]
It was regarded not merely as affording
the means of converting other metals into
Gold and as providing remedies for all
Maladies; but as laying open the
great secret of Nature and as explaining
the phenomena of the Earth of the
sea of the Air and of the subterranean
mineral [deletion]kindom[/deletion] kingdom.
[person]person_061|Albertus Magnus[/person] and [person]person_324|Roger Bacon[/person]
who are the first persons recorded as
applying themselves to experiment in
the dark ages seem both to have been
guided by very philosophical views
and to have had as their principle

[page]13|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00013|dnp16c11pp|94869430[/page]
objects the advancement of Science.
[person]person_324|the elder Bacon[/person] confesses in his great
work that He gained the foundation of
his knowledge from the Arabian writers
upon whom he bestows high and
unqualified praise.
This great man evidently studied
[underline]Nature[/underline] and the production of the Earth
with the views of a philosopher but
his knowledge was so superior as to be
unintelligible in the age in which he
lived. The wonders produced by chemistry
were referred by the people to [deletion]evil[/deletion]
[deletion]spirits[/deletion] the agency of evil spirits

[page]14|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00014|dnp16c12pp|94869431[/page]
and a very short time after He had
written a book to prove the [underline]nonexistence[/underline]
[underline]of Magic[/underline] He was himself persecuted
as an [underline]enchanter[/underline], and He was imprisoned
in 1278 by the Franciscans for having brought
the order into disrepute by pretending
to [underline]natural wisdom[/underline] and by exercising
[underline]unholy[/underline] and [underline]supernatural powers[/underline]
[person]person_324|Roger Bacon[/person] appears to have
made use of the philosophical and
experimental method of the [misc]misc_273|Saracens[/misc]
without following any of the

[page]15|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00015|dnp16c13pp|94869432[/page]
absurdities of their doctrines, He had seen
admirable changes produced in bodies and
He knew not the limits of the operation of Nature
By Him the [underline]production[/underline] of Gold and the
transmutation of [underline]Metals[/underline] were considered only
as [underline]objects[/underline] worthy of investigation; but
He never affirmed confidently concerning them.
He had made many important discoveries
and particularly that of [misc]misc_680|one expensive compound[/misc]
similar to Gunpowder -
And yet he seldom suffered his imagination
to cloud his reason and He was no
enthusiast with regard to the merit of
his inventions.-

[page]16|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00016|dnp16c14pp|94869433[/page]
He possessed the modest and dignified feeling
of Science; but most of the Alchemists who
flourished in the next century were of a very
different complexion. They formed themselves
into a fraternity They professed to be
in possession of great and important [unclear]secrets[/unclear]
They connected a peculiar mysticism
with their philosophical doctrines.
They attached to Alchemy a language
similar to that which had been employed
in the [person]person_085|Platonic[/person] philosophy and they
pretended [deletion]to[/deletion] not only [deletion]to[/deletion] a knowledge
of the materials of the Globe and the

[page]17|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00017|dnp16c15pp|94869434[/page]
changes of things but likewise to an
[deletion]organization[/deletion] acquaintance with the elemen[insertion]ts[/insertion]
and the spiritual powers by which they
supposed these were governed.-
The Arabians had blended in their
philosophy many brilliant superstitions
concerning the agency of a class of beings
supposed to be superior to Man and
possessed of great knowledge and of
high power.-
And the notion of fa[insertion]i[/insertion]ries and [misc]misc_211|Genii[/misc]
which have been depicted with so much
vividness of fancy and loveliness of
description in [otherwork]otherwork_123|the thousand and one[line]nights[/otherwork] seems to have been adopted under a
new form.-

[page]18|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00018|dnp16c16pp|94869435[/page]
By the adepts of this period [underline]in Europe[/underline] 
who though they altered the denominations
[underline]of the [deletion][unclear]serif[/unclear][/deletion] spiritual[/underline] [underline]Agents created[/underline]
by the fancy of [underline]the orientalists.[/underline] still
attribute to them similar attributes and
similar relations to Man.-
[person]person_069|Agrippa[/person] in his work on the [underline]occult[/underline]
[underline]Sciences[/underline] endeavours to devellope a general
system of the philosophy of the Earth
and He begins by supposing that all
things on the terrestrial Globe are
under the protection of influences residing
in the stars and of Good and evil [misc]misc_211|Genii[/misc]
and that true knowledge can be derived
only from a communication with those

[page]19|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00019|dnp16c17pp|94869436[/page]
spiritual beings.
[person]person_069|Agrippa[/person] considered [underline]fire[/underline] as the great
active principle in Nature and from
its operation upon earth which He regards
as a passive element He conceived the
great appearances of the external world
produced.-
Water and Air He thought were more
capable of being converted into each other
and yet He considered this as a vital
principle which existed in almost all
substances and as essential to their
composition and their nature.-

[page]20|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00020|dnp16c18pp|94869437[/page]
This last passage is one of the few
philosophical ones in his work[deletion]s[/deletion] the
most worthy of notice: his pages are
generally filled with the grossest absurdities
It is difficult to conjecture from them
whether he is self deluded or whether
he is endeavouring to deceive others
whether his imagination was distempered
or whether he was attempting an
imposture
[person]person_069|Agrippa[/person] was born at [place]place_1312|Cologne[/place] in 1463
after the publication of his system
he was of course considered as a Magician
by the vulgar and a number of idle

[page]21|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00021|dnp16c19pp|94869438[/page]
tales exist with regard to his History
He asserted that He was in possession of
the [misc]misc_381|Philosophers stone[/misc] yet He was always
miserably poor - He affirmed that He
had spirits under his command who were
capable of conveying him from place
to place and yet he passed the last
years of his life in [insertion]the[/insertion] prison of [place]place_356|Lyons:[/place]
where he was confined not because He
professed Magic but because He had
violently abused [person]person_1055|the Queen Mother of France.[/person]
The general systems of the famous
[person]person_509|[underline]paracelsus[/underline][/person] seem to have differed
very little from that of [person]person_069|Agrippa[/person] -

[page]22|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00022|dnp16c20pp|94869439[/page]
He supposed the elements under the
influence of the stars and that all
the spaces in the universe void of
matter were filled with peculiar [underline]spiritual[/underline]
[underline]beings.[/underline]
And He has made sure of the very names
which have been so much employed in the
machinery of modern Poetry. Then he regarded
the [deletion]syp[/deletion] Sylphs and Gnomes as belonging
to the Earth and spectres to the air
and salamanders to the fire -
[person]person_509|Paracelsus[/person] introduced [chemical]chemical_037|Sulphur[/chemical] and
[chemical]chemical_012|Mercury[/chemical] into his Theory as principles
composing the metals and He regarded

[page]23|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00023|dnp16c21pp|94869440[/page]
[underline]Animals[/underline] as chiefly constituted of Air and
vegetables of Earth.
The life of this man who was born in
[underline][place]place_198|Switzerland[/place][/underline] in 1493 was full of the most
extraordinary events. He travelled through
most of the Countries of Europe and Asia
and even passed a considerable time in
[place]place_222|Affrica[/place] seeking wherever he whent
for secrets in Chemistry, and professing
to cure all maladies.-
His enthusiasm almost supplied his want
of genius and confidence in his own
powers
He was appointed to the professor at
Bale but he soon contrived to disgust
the Magistrates and to gain a dismissal

[page]24|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00024|dnp16c22pp|94869441[/page]
He was fond of living only amongst the lower
order of the people: and from associating
continually with the inferior, He acquired
the most offensive vanity the most insup-
-portable arrogance. He abused the physicians
of his time in the grossest terms.
He substituted chemical preparations for
vegetable medicines. And he publicly burns
the words of [person]person_1056|[underline]Avicenna[/underline][/person] saying that
there were no other masters in medicine
but Nature and himself.-
He passed his last days in wandering
about in [place]place_324|Germany[/place]. and when He was
reproached on account of his way of life

[page]25|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00025|dnp16c23pp|94869442[/page]
He proudly answered that it was not fit
for a person born to succor the whole of
Mankind to attach himself to any one
spot and that He who was destined to
read the book of Nature ought not to
have his eyes fixed upon the same [underline]leaf[/underline].
[person]person_221|[underline]Van Helmont[/underline][/person] of [place]place_1147|Brussels[/place] like [person]person_509|[underline]paracelsus[/underline][/person]
was a mystic but He combined much
more sound philosophy in his views of
Nature and of the Earth -
He was a diligent experimenter and a
minute observer and some of his [deletion]research[/deletion]
researches led to important results.-

[page]26|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00026|dnp16c24pp|94869443[/page]
He was the first person who supposed that
[chemical]chemical_078|elastic fluid[/chemical] existed different from the
Air of the Atmosphere and [underline]from him[/underline]
we derive the modern [underline]chemical[/underline] name [underline]of Gas[/underline]
He likewise invented another denomination
[misc]misc_852|[underline]Blas[/underline][/misc] which is not quite so intelligible -
He considered it as of a much finer
nature than Air; and as being derived
by the Earth and from the sun and stars -
[person]person_221|Van Helmont[/person] made some very laborious
experiments to prove that water was
capable of being converted into [underline]Earth[/underline]
and He [underline]revived [/underline]the the doctrine of
[person]person_609|Thales[/person] that it was the general productive
principle.-

[page]27|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00027|dnp16c25pp|94869444[/page]
The Sixteenth century was the [underline]great[/underline]
[underline]era[/underline] in which the mystical adept flourished.
The famous [misc]misc_410|Rosicrucian[/misc] Society seems
to have been established about this time
by them.
And the history of this Institution is secret
as obscure as that of the kindred Sect of
the modern illuminees.-
It would be of little use and foreign
to the objects of these lectures to enter upon
an examination of all the writings published
on Alchemy in different parts of Europe
by Valentine by Fludd by [person]person_1105|Boemen[/person] and others

[page]28|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00028|dnp16c26pp|94869445[/page]
And I should not have given any [unclear]sketch[/unclear]
even of the doctrines of the adepts
had not some of their labours been
immediately connected with the progress
of true [underline]chemical[/underline] and [underline]geological[/underline]
[underline]knowledge[/underline].-
They were experimenters with false
views but they nevertheless sometimes
develloped truth.-
They were indefatigable in their
research and they had ascertained
a number of the most curious properties
of bodies without being able to account
philosophically for their effects -

[page]29|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00029|dnp16c27pp|94869446[/page]
Though visionaries they sometimes acted
according to the dictates of right reason
As persons who walk in their sleep [deletion]perform[/deletion]
sometimes perform in a proper manner
the common occupations of life.-
The facts scattered amongst their absurdities
were valuable in the highest degree to
the philosophical men who came after
them.
And a true and enlightened [underline]science[/underline]
arose by degree and amidst clouds
and obscurity from the [insertion]furnaces[/insertion][deletion]furnaces[/deletion]
of the [underline]Alchemists[/underline].

[page]30|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00030|dnp16c28pp|94869447[/page]
|_George [person]person_062|Agricola[/person] was the [underline]first person[/underline]
who published [deletion]on[/deletion] practical mineralogy
and on Geological chemistry in the
16 century. His work on the metals
contain a number of important [deletion]facts[/deletion]
truths which are always detailed with
peculiar candour and modesty -
He describes the general [underline]position[/underline] of
the veins in the great mineral
countries of [place]place_324|Germany[/place].
He gives a natural history of ores and
a particular account of the manner
in which the are worked and in [underline]none[/underline]
[underline]of his details [/underline]does He enter upon

[page]31|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00031|dnp16c29pp|94869448[/page]
wild speculations and He has treated the
professed adepts of his age with a cool
and dignified [deletion]un[/deletion] indifference. -
[person]person_1059|Lazarus Erckern[/person] assay Master General
to the German mines was Co[insertion]n[/insertion]temporary [underline]with[/underline]
[underline][person]person_062|Agricola[/person][/underline]. His work on the art of assaying
has been translated into English by [person]person_1060|Sir[line]John Pettus[/person] and it contains much
valuable matter with regard to metallur-
-gical Chemistry.
Both [person]person_062|Agricola[/person] and [person]person_1059|Erckern[/person] considered
the metals as incapable of being transmuted
into each other and they regarded
them as produced by certain operations of
Nature which cannot be imitated by
artificial means.-

[page]32|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00032|dnp16c30pp|94869449[/page]
The period in which these two
[underline]mineralogists[/underline]wrote was the great era
of improvement in the general methods
of the natural sciences.-
It was the period in which the
death blow was given to Alchemy by
[person]person_757|Gassendi[/person] and [deletion]Kelp[/deletion] [person]person_363|Kepler[/person] who both
answered for Fludd the last public
defender of the Rosicrusians -
It was the period in which [underline][person]person_283|Gallileo[/person][/underline]
pursued the paths of experimental
enquiry; And in which [person]person_124|the second[line]illustrous Bacon[/person] had the honour of

[page]33|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00033|dnp16c31pp|94869450[/page]
establishing [underline]the Sciences[/underline] upon their
true and immutable foundations.-
Many scientific persons [person]person_124|[underline]before Bacon[/underline][/person]
had pursued the method of Experiment
in all its precision, many had dared
to despise the logic and forms of the
ancients, but He was the [underline]first[/underline]
[underline]philosopher[/underline] who laid down plans for
extending knowledge of universal application
who ventured to assert that all the sciences
could be nothing more than expressions
of facts and that the first step towards
the attainment of real discovery was
the humiliating confession of [underline]ignorance[/underline]

[page]34|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00034|dnp16c32pp|94869451[/page]
Bacon was prepared by Nature by
education and by his habit of study for
effecting the great revolution in philosophy
His knowledge was extensive his instances
were copious. His Genius was equally
capable of develloping the lighter and
the more profound relations of things.
He professed a strong feeling but it
was uniformly directed by [underline]reason[/underline] -
He was gifted with a vivid imagination
but it was modified by a most correct
taste - 
The influence of rank and of situation
assisted his views - The public was prepared
to receive them, and he was enabled

[page]35|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00035|dnp16c33pp|94869452[/page]
to devellope his opinions with full
confidence that they would be adopted
with reverence even in his own time and
that they would carry his memory into
future ages with [underline]great[/underline] and [underline]with[/underline]
unchanging Glory.-
+ The pursuit of the new method of investigat[insertion]ion[/insertion]
in a very short time wholly altered the
face of every department of Natural
Knowledge but their influence was in
no case more distinct that in the advance[insertion]ment[/insertion]
of Geology and chemistry; though much
labour had been bestowed upon these
extensive fields of investigation they
had hitherto as we have seen been little
productive.-

[page]36|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00036|dnp16c34pp|94869453[/page]
Speculation had been misplaced observation
confined and experiment principally
directed rather towards impossible than
to practicable things.
in the [underline]novel system[/underline] [underline]hypotheses[/underline] was
exploded except as a guide to [underline]actual[/underline]
[deletion]truths[/deletion] [underline]trials[/underline] - Combinations of thoughts
were considered as truths only when
conformable [underline]to Nature[/underline] and not [deletion]merely[/deletion]
when they merely expressed the caprices
of the imagination and those enquiries
only were regarded as valuable which
were made upon the hidden sensible
properties of things and upon the
existing relations of facts.

[page]37|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00037|dnp16c35pp|94869454[/page]
