[underline]Science[/underline].

[page]38|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00038|dnp16c36pp|94869455[/page]
He [deletion]applied[/deletion][insertion]devoted[/insertion] his attention equally to the great
[deletion]In chemistry he develloped with a[/deletion]
laws of the globe considered as a part of the
planetary system; & to the minute changes
[deletion]rapid yet penetrating view the general[/deletion]
& imperceptitible alterations of the surface -
[deletion]History of [underline]combustion[/underline][/deletion] - His opinions
upon terrestrial motions are marked by a singular
And his hypotheses of Earthquakes and
volcanoes is scarcely exceeded by any of
the refinements of Theory in modern times.
Few men have done more than [person]person_246|Hooke[/person]
and few have been more neglected and
one of the principal reasons is that
He was the contemporary of [person]person_036|[underline]Newton[/underline][/person]
whose just Glory and whose splendid
discoveries concerning the great laws
of the universe absorbed the attention
of the philosophers of the age and

[page]39|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00039|dnp16c37pp|94869456[/page]
and made them almost regardless
of inferior inventions.
[person]person_246|Hooke[/person] in the [underline]geological speculations[/underline]
which were published after his death
assuming as a fact the existence of
[underline]shells and the[/underline] [deletion]and the[/deletion] remains of
[underline]marine[/underline] animals in rocks and in hills
of [underline]considerable elevation[/underline] draws the
conclusions, that these strata must have
been at some period covered by the sea
And after reasoning upon the general
[underline]effects of Earthquakes[/underline] and of Volcanic
explosions He infers that there are
no causes in nature more probable than

[page]40|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00040|dnp16c38pp|94869457[/page]
these for the elevation of land of rock
and of mountains from the bosom
of the waters.
He brings forward many chemical
instances "to shew" that water is capable
of dissolving and of depositing stoney
matter and that its agency is fully
adequate to the formation of strata.
And He shews that both in modern and
in ancient times several cases have
occurred of Islands and of tracts of Land
rising out of the sea in consequence
of submarine Volcanoes -
The ideas of [person]person_246|Hooke[/person] are conceived with
boldness and develloped with precision,

[page]41|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00041|dnp16c39pp|94869458[/page]
In many principal parts of Theory He
had anticipated the modern [person]person_085|Platonic[/person]
Philosophers: He seems however to have
restrained his imagination. He has
contented himself with demonstrating a
certain part of the existing order of
Nature without attempting a general
system of the past change of the Globe
and of its future destiny -
Beccher lived at the same period
as [person]person_246|Hooke[/person] like [person]person_246|Hooke[/person] He devoted his life
to Science; but He selected one
department and directed to Geological
[deletion]Gelogi[/deletion] chemistry the whole of the
power of his [deletion]genius[/deletion]mind -

[page]42|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00042|dnp16c40pp|94869459[/page]
In his book called [otherwork]otherwork_317|subterranean philosophy[/otherwork]
published in latin in 1669
He has given some very beautiful
details with regard to the Mineral
Kingdom and has offered views of
Theory perfectly new - his ideas
concerning combination and decomposit
are of the most accurate nature
his notion of an inflamable principle
formed the foundation of the hypothesis
of Hall - He gave to chemical philosophy
new dominions and new instruments of
investigation and He attempted to form
a [deletion]general[/deletion] Theory in which all the
operations of Nature should be explained

[page]43|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00043|dnp16c41pp|94869460[/page]
illustrated by experiments of human invention
Beccher with the sound judgment of
a true philosopher assumes a certain
primary order of things resulting from
the creation of the Globe and He applies
only to the solution of the phaenomena
of the change, which have since taken
place
[underline]Water in the mineral kingdom[/underline] and
elastic vapours He considers as the great
agents which have altered the position
of strata and the direction of metalic
veins and from the decomposition of
certain rocks by these natural agents
he supposes that new ones have been
formed of a much [underline]softer nature[/underline] and

[page]44|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00044|dnp16c42pp|94869461[/page]
fitted to become soils and to support
vegetable Life -
Beccher was born at spire in 1645
He was for some time professor of medicine
at [place]place_1128|Bavaria[/place] but He was driven from
[place]place_324|Germany[/place] by envy and persecution.
[place]place_121|England[/place] became his adopted Country He
was patronized by the great [person]person_103|Boyle[/person] in
consequence of whose liberality He was
enabled to study mineralogy in
[place]place_021|Cornwall[/place] to further his experimental
researches and to produce some of those
works on Natural Science which
will always confer honour on
his name -

[page]45|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00045|dnp16c43pp|94869462[/page]
Hook and Beccher had contented themselves
with [underline]partial views[/underline];
And the celebrated [person]person_1005|[underline]Leibnitz[/underline][/person] is the first
philosopher who attempted a [underline]general[/underline]
[underline]system[/underline] of Geology -
In his - [otherwork]otherwork_318|[insertion]Protogaea[/insertion][/otherwork] published in 1693 He enters
upon the [underline]great doctrines[/underline] relating to [underline]the Globe[/underline]
the primary creation, [underline]the deluge[/underline] the changes
that have been since produced and that
will be produced in [underline]future ages[/underline] -
He assumes as the foundation of his reasoning
the account of the creation given in the
[underline]sacred writings[/underline];-
And He attempts to shew that the
Globe at its origin must have existed in

[page]46|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00046|dnp16c44pp|94869463[/page]
a state of igneous fusion in consequence of
which it assumed its [underline]spherical form[/underline];
The heavier substances such as the metals
He supposes to have occupied the centre
and He conceives that the Rocks; which
crystalized at first in regular strata were
afterwards broken and raised into mountains
by explosions taking place from beneath
and the Chasms produced and filled with
metalic veins.-
The water which at first existed as
highly rarified vapour He supposed to have
been by degrees condensed and from its
action in its heated state upon the

[page]47|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00047|dnp16c45pp|94869464[/page]
Land He conceives that a part of the
surface was decomposed broken down and
converted into a soil on which by the
Almighty [unclear]fiat[/unclear] vegetables and Animals
were made to exist and the whole cloathed
with beauty and rendered [underline]subservient[/underline]
to the purposes of [deletion]life[/deletion] [underline]the last[/underline] created
and most perfect [underline]of beings[/underline]
[person]person_1005|Leibnitz[/person] supposes that there may have
been two causes for the deluge:-
The elevation of Land in the former bed
of the Ocean in consequence of explosions
from the central ignited mass: and
[underline]the passage of the tail of a Comet[/underline] -

[page]48|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00048|dnp16c46pp|94869465[/page]
[underline]through the Atmosphere loaded with[/underline]
[underline]aqueous[/underline] vapour -
By the first cause He explains the
passage in [otherwork]otherwork_281|Geneis[/otherwork] "The fountains of the
great deep were broken up and by the
second the other sentence the windows
of heaven were opened and the rain
was upon the Earth for forty days
and forty Nights.-
[person]person_1005|Leibnitz[/person] supposes that the principal
changes which have taken place since
[underline]the deluge[/underline] have depended either upon
Volcanic fires: or great inundations
from the Ocean and He conceives

[page]49|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00049|dnp16c47pp|94869466[/page]
that fire and Water are Counterballancing
powers by which an order of things
similar to the present will be maintained
till the great and general conflagration
Such is the doctrine of the [otherwork]otherwork_318|Protogaea[/otherwork]
as found in the excellent edition of the
works of [person]person_1005|Leibnitz[/person] by [person]person_1061|M[superscript]r[/superscript] Dutens.-[/person]
The work it self is in the highest degree
deserving of a minute examination -
It is worthy of the Genius of the Illustrious
Author:-
When facts are stated in it they are
detailed with clearness and accuracy
and where Hypotheses are indulged

[page]50|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00050|dnp16c48pp|94869467[/page]
in; they mark an imagination fertile
in novelty and pregnant with
bold conceptions.-
That his [underline]reasoning is not always[/underline] convincing
rater depends upon his endeavouring to
resolve problems concerning which there
no data than upon any imperfection
in his methods -
The subject which He has undertaken
[underline]to discuss[/underline] is one almost above the powers
of the human mind.
It required high talents to produce
any philosophical views with regard
to it and the abilities of [deletion]Lebn[/deletion]

[page]51|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00051|dnp16c49pp|94869468[/page]
[person]person_1005|Leibnitz[/person] where they have not develloped
actual [underline]truth[/underline] have uniformaly produced
some brilliant semblance to reality in
which the fancy always and sometimes
even the [underline]reason[/underline] can dwell with delight
The [otherwork]otherwork_318|protogea[/otherwork] has been very little known
but many writers appear to have borrowed
from it -
[person]person_519|Whiston[/person] adopted the Idea of a comet
having produced the Deluge: and has
endeavoured to prove it from mathematical
deductions - His treatise is however very
much inferior in precision to that of
the prussian philosopher and contains
no ideas remarkable either for strength or novelty

[page]52|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00052|dnp16c50pp|94869469[/page]
[deletion]An other system which appeared about[/deletion]
[deletion]the same time as that of [person]person_1005|Leibnitz[/person][/deletion]
Another system which appeared about the
same time as that of [person]person_1005|Leibnitz[/person] has excited
infinitely more attention in [place]place_159|Britain[/place]
I mean the [otherwork]otherwork_319|sacred Theory of the [deletion]New[/deletion][/otherwork]
Earth by [person]person_1001|[underline]D[superscript]r[/superscript] Burnet[/underline][/person]
In this work the Globe is supposed
to have been created without irregularities
[underline]perfectly spherical[/underline] and smooth having
neither Hills Mountains nor Vallies -
The land is supposed to Have been
equally diffused above the Ocean
and to have covered it as a thin

[page]53|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00053|dnp16c51pp|94869470[/page]
Crust and the deluge is considered as
having been occasioned by the breaking
down of the land into the great abyss
beneath an event which He supposes to
have produced all the varieties of Sea
and Earth that present exist the
formation of Islands and the great
[underline]elevation of Continents[/underline] -
Burnet paints with all the feeling
of an enthusiast the [underline]delightful state[/underline]
of the inhabitants of the Globe before
the deluge in his hypotheses as there
could have been no variety of Seasons
He conceives that they must have
enjoyed a [underline]perpetual Spring[/underline];

[page]54|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00054|dnp16c52pp|94869471[/page]
that the face of Heaven and the Sun
and the Stars must have been exhibited
to them in unclouded beauty.
And that the whole of the Earth
must have been green with perpetual
vegetation.
Burnet saw none of the errors of his
system - He did not perceive that
without the action of the waters of the
sea upon the atmosphere there could
be no rain no dews no rivers and
consequently no plants and no animal life
His mode of accounting for the moistening
of the Earth by the filtration of water
through the solid matter and its

[page]55|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00055|dnp16c53pp|94869472[/page]
elevation into the air is [underline]perfectly inadmiss[/underline]-
[underline]ible[/underline] and every one must allow that the
feeling and taste of the [misc]misc_853|Antediluvians[/misc]
must have been very different from ours
If they could derive more pleasure from
the contemplation of a flat surface and
an uniform sky than from the view
of the variety of hill and dale of
mountain and river scenery and
the ever varying appearances of clouds
[person]person_1062|[underline]D[superscript]r[/superscript] Keil[/underline][/person] in his [otherwork]otherwork_320|examination of the[line][underline]sacred Theory[/underline][/otherwork] has distinctly proved
that it is wholly incompatable with the
general laws of the Globe and not
conformable in the slightest degree to facts -

[page]56|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00056|dnp16c54pp|94869473[/page]
As a poetical Romance it is highly
interesting and entertaining but as
a philosophical opinion it is wholly
unworthy of [deletion]opinion[/deletion] attention and it
affords one proof amongst many others
of the folly of attempts to wrest the
meaning of the sacred writings
which express general truths so as
to make them serve as supports for
hypotheses of human invention so as
to blend them with the visions
and fancies of men - _|

[page]57|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00057|dnp16c55pp|94869474[/page]
The last system which I shall mention in
this Lecture is that of [person]person_266|[underline]Buffon[/underline][/person].-
|_One of the most singular and extraordinary
productions of the human mind, beauties and
defects are blended in it and it is complete
with ingenuity and with errors.
|_[person]person_266|Buffons[/person] idea of the primary state of the Globe
is wholly borrowed [person]person_1005|[underline]from Leibnitz[/underline].[/person] He conceives
it to have existed in igneous fusion; but despising
the modern opinion of the Author of the
[otherwork]otherwork_318|Protogaea[/otherwork] that such was its [underline]primary creation[/underline] -
He supposes it to have been produced from
the ruins of another system to have been
carried off from the Sun by the powerful
impulse of a Comet and to have been moved -

[page]58|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00058|dnp16c56pp|94869475[/page]
into its present orbit by and the
force of gravity -
He fixes the era at which this great event
is supposed to have taken place at a
distance of time quite inconceivable -
And He imagines three [underline]different epochs[/underline]
in [underline]the history[/underline] of the cooling of the
surface [underline]before[/underline] [underline]Marine Animals[/underline] existed
and five epochs before it was fitted for
the residence of Land Animals & of Man -
[person]person_266|Buffon[/person] brings forward two principal
arguments in the support of his htypothesis
and they are now both known to be
founded upon false principles -

[page]59|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00059|dnp16c57pp|94869476[/page]
His first is that the temperature of the
Earth is found higher the farther we
penetrate beneath the surface
The second is that the surface of the
Earth is composed of matters which are
almost all capable of being [chemical]chemical_509|vitrified[/chemical]
by Heat -
Now it is well ascertained that except
in [underline]volcanic countries[/underline] at a considerable
depth is the mean temperature of [underline]the[/underline]
[underline]Atmosphere[/underline] and that it varies according
to that mean in all the different
climates so that it is evidently produced
not by internal but by external causes
not, by a [deletion]cont[/deletion] central fire but by the solar
rays and the heat of the Air -

[page]60|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00060|dnp16c58pp|94869477[/page]
With regard to the other propositions
it is certain that the greater number
of [underline]our Rocks[/underline] are wholly incapable of
being fused by any Heat that we
are able to apply to them;
And though it is not improbable in
a temperature such as that of the Sun
they would become liquid; yet we
have no right to make inference merely
for the sake of forming [underline]a Theory[/underline]
For a theory ought in all cases to be
+ not an expression of conjecture but
an arrangement of facts.
The ideas of [person]person_266|Buffon[/person] concerning the
changes of the Globe that are now

[page]61|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00061|dnp16c59pp|94869478[/page]
taking place and the general order
[underline]of Nature[/underline] are scarcely less bold or less
visionary than his notions concerning
the origin of things -
He conceives that the land and the sea
are continually changing places. that
from the action of rains of Rivers and of
torrents the solid matter of the land is
constantly divided decomposed and deposited
in the Ocean.
In which carried by currents towards
the equator it is again accumulated
in strata and formed by the [unclear]powers[/unclear]
of aqueous consolidation into new Rocks
and new mountains which rise at
length above the waves and offer

[page]62|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00062|dnp16c60pp|94869479[/page]
a due compensation for the destruction
of parts of ancient continents and Islands
This Hypothesis in which the waters
of the Atmosphere are supposed to be
the destroying cause and the water
of the sea the regenerating cause
of [underline]the solid land[/underline] is supported by the
Author with considerable address and
ingenuity -
He endeavours to prove from the
shells and remains of fishes found in
some parts of high mountains that
the present continents must have been
formed in the bed of the ocean -

[page]63|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00063|dnp16c61pp|94869480[/page]
[insertion][unclear]He endeavours to[/unclear][/insertion]He endeavours to shew that some of the Islands
under the equator have been very lately
raised - And He brings forward many
accurate instances which demonstrate
that the sea has gained upon the land
to some extent in many different
parts of Europe.-
I shall not at present enter upon a full
discussion of these opinions for they will
again occupy our attention in the
examination of a much more comprehensive
and [otherwork]otherwork_097|more artfully constructed theory[/otherwork] that
of [person]person_125|D[superscript]r[/superscript] Hutton.[/person]
I shall merely offer a few general
observations upon them.-

[page]64|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00064|dnp16c62pp|94869481[/page]
With regard to the idea that our present
land was formed in the bosom of the
sea by the mere action of water is
is one that may be controverted and
overturned with ease.-
The greatest portion of our high rocks
and elevated mountains are chrystalized
masses containing no organic remains
and not arranged in layers and they
consist of matter wholly incapable of
being consolidated by water such is
[chemical]chemical_092|Granite[/chemical] which forms a considerable
part of the [place]place_247|Alps[/place] which constitutes
the great mountains of [place]place_235|Scotland[/place] and
the hills and cliffs of [place]place_021|Cornwall[/place].-

[page]65|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00065|dnp16c63pp|94869482[/page]
And stratified rocks even which seem
themselves to have been deposited by
water are often blended with rocks of
another description so as rather to indicate
a great inundation and rapid transit
of the ocean over [underline]the land[/underline] than a
gradual and [underline]quite deposition[/underline] of the
solid matter of the earth in the bed of the sea.
It is impossible to doubt that in the
lapse of ages some slight [unclear]dimunition[/unclear]
of our mountains must take place from
the [underline]agency of rivers[/underline] but there are many
causes in Nature which appears
to counteract the effect.

[page]66|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00066|dnp16c64pp|94869483[/page]
Centuries nearly have passed away and
no material change in the form of the
solid matter of the Globe has taken
place in consequence of this agency.
From the most accurate observation it
appears nearly a hundred years would
be consumed before a single inch of
a Rock like that which this represents
or of [place]place_1315|Mount Blanch[/place] would be lost and
with regard to the ultimate termination
of such effects it is almost ridiculous
to reason seriously -
Man attached to the Globe has a limited
sphere of action limited faculties and
but a short period for the employment

[page]67|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00067|dnp16c65pp|94869484[/page]
of them -
He was not intended to waste his time in
guesses concerning what is to take place
in infinite duration but He was rather
born to reason from the past and the
present concerning his immediate and
future destinies and philosophy as well
as in common life He [deletion]only[/deletion] ought only
to be guided by certainties by distinct
probabilities or by strong analogies -
To conclude after censuring [person]person_266|M. Buffons[/person]
wilder speculations it would be unfair
to deny to him the highest praise for
order of arrangement splendor of description
and brilliancy of stile -

[page]68|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00068|dnp16c66pp|94869485[/page]
He has adorned a subject of the most
abstracted kind in the refined charms
and elegancies of literature and He
has bestowed on it an interest which
it had never professed before.
His merit in this respect is
transcendent - there is nothing highly
difficult in the task of delineating
[underline]Human character[/underline] in painting the
passions and affections of the mind,
with eloquence and with feeling -
for these belong to all minds, all
climes and all ages and their
effects are [deletion]universal[/deletion] universal -

[page]69|MS-DAVY-11603-000-00069|dnp16c67pp|94869486[/page]
But to cloath [insertion]the[/insertion] dull and dead objects
of a speculative branch of science in
the form of beauty and to infuse into
them animation and life -
This is indeed a work which the strongest
genius only can accomplish; and it
is a work in which [person]person_266|Buffon[/person] has
perfectly [underline]succeeded[/underline].-

